{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "buddhism-expert",
    "senderColor": "red",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Option A — keep \"character\" throughout",
    "content": "**Option A.** Keep \"(constitutive) character\" throughout, with a TN acknowledging the departure.\n\nOption B creates a worse problem than the one it solves. If the Laozi block quote says \"virtue\" and the author's analysis says \"character,\" the reader has to track that these are the SAME word (德) being rendered two different ways. The author's entire argument is about tracing how 德 is constructed bottom-up through the sequence 礼→义→仁→德→道. If \"virtue\" appears in the quote and \"character\" appears in the analysis, the reversal structure — which is the whole point — becomes harder to follow, not easier.\n\nThe standard translators are translating the Laozi AS the Laozi. We are translating the Laozi AS QUOTED BY this author for a specific argumentative purpose. The author's use of the passage is not exegetical — they explicitly say so. The translation should serve the author's argument, not D.C. Lau's.\n\nThe TN is the right place to acknowledge the departure: \"Standard translations render 德 as 'virtue' (Lau, Chan, Legge). We use 'character' to reflect the author's constructivist analysis, in which 德 denotes the defining properties attributed to a category rather than moral excellence.\""
  }
}
